description: These kaomojis screwed up some how and now they have to apologize which kind of sucks. If you screw up too you can use one of these to hopefully lighten the mood.
feature: A lot of these Japanese emoticons are supposed to represent someone bowing down because they’re apologizing or possibly thanking someone for something. These use the letter m to show hands and the eyes are low to the ground.

description: These kaomojis are confused about something. Why they’re confused we may never know. You might even say I’m confused about why they’re confused. What does that even mean? I think I need to go lay down for a bit because of all this confusion…
feature: For confused Japanese emoticons you can use ・ or ◎ for blank looking eyes. ゞ makes a perfect arm scratching a head to indicate thought. You can also add question marks to any of these to show even more confusion. You can also use щ or ლ as raised hands to make emoticons that look as if they’re shouting “Why!?”.

description: These kaomojis are all of the other Japanese emoticon animals that didn’t fit in any of the other categories. There’s snakes, mice, various rodents and mammals and much more.
feature: There’s a big section of different hedgehogs and recently spiders have started appearing here as well.

description: These are some evil looking kaomojis. We’ll not all of them are completely evil. Some might just be a little bit devious but I’d definitely stay away from those ones with the pitchforks and the devil tails. A lot of these emoticons would be great for Halloween I think.
feature: For evil looking Japanese emoticons you pretty much want to use ｀ and ´ for the eyes. You can use pretty much anything else for a mouth and other elements and it’ll still look evil.

description: These kaomojis are angry and man there are a ton of them. What did you guys do to make so many of these so angry? We’ll that’s not important since none of these are actually something real with real feelings or anything like that… What was I talking about? Oh yes, angry Japanese emoticons. If you’re angry and you want to express that anger of yours then these are the emoticons that you want to use! You’ll find all kinds of kaomoji with varying levels of anger.
feature: For most angry Japanese emoticons just use > and < for eyes. You can also use ≧ or ≦. Two ¬’s makes sort of a displeased looking face. You can also use slashes or ヽ and ノ to make it look like the emoticon is throwing up it’s hands in anger and if you really want to express anger use a 凸 for a middle finger. 益 also makes a fantastic mouth for angry Japanese emoticons.

description: Just when I think I must have seen all the possible bear kaomoji emoticons that exist I find even more. It’s almost scary how many different Japanese emoticon bears there are. They’re all really cute too. I’m especially impressed with the Harry Potter bears.
feature: The main thing with Japanese bear emoticons is the mouth. You want to use (ｴ), ㉨ or possibly a ω. Everything else is pretty much the same as other Japanese emoticons. There’s also the other sort of small type of bear made with ᶘ and ᶅ for the sides of the head.

description: These are other somewhat random Japanese emoticons that didn’t really fit into other categories or I couldn’t quite figure out what they were trying to show. You can feel free to use these as well if you like them and if you find any of them that you know should be in a different category let me know so I can get that fixed right away!

This is a category of Japanese emoticons that is completely unique to this site. Random Japanese emoticons are simply randomly generated Japanese emoticons. A lot of randomly generated emoticons look dumb but sometimes you get some really awesome looking ones like these.
There’s even a pretty good amount of kaomoji pig emoticons! Some of these pigs are pretty cute too.
feature: The main thing for Japanese pig emoticons is the snout which you can make with two 0s, Os, os or a ∞. You can do pretty much anything else you want for the rest of the face.

description: Something has these kaomoji emoticons worried. I’m not sure what they’re worried about and I hope everything works out well for them in the end. Who am I kidding, they’re Japanese emoticons, what do they have to worry about?! Wait, they’re not even real so of course they have nothing to worry about! Unless that’s the very thing that has them so worried! This is complicated… I’m not sure what to think anymore…
feature: Anyways, if you want to express some kind of worry or if something has you feeling some slight unease then these are the kaomoji that you’re going to want to use.

description: These kaomojis just don’t care and they want you to know. If you just don’t care and you want to throw your hands up in the air and say meh (but on the Internet!) then these are the emoticons for you!
feature: The key to making Japanese emoticons that just don’t care is pretty much just having arms pointing upwards with , /, ┗, ┛ or ノ. It’s probably even better if you take some smug emoticons and give them the meh treatment.

description: This category contains kaomoji that are fighting, kicking, punching, hurting each other, inflicting other various forms of violence and wielding weapons such as guns or swords. I was starting to collect enough of these kinds of Japanese emoticons that I felt we needed a new category for them instead of just adding them to the other actions page or maybe the angry page. A lot of these emoticons are jerks.
feature: You can take pretty much any kaomoji emoticon and add و و for raised fists and suddenly that emoticon is getting ready to fight. You can also add a ┌┛to show the emoticon kicking something. Or you can grab any of the gun and sword props from any of these emoticons and use them to make your own. There’s even a crossed swords character ⚔ which is pretty cool.

description: These poor kaomoji emoticons have taken all they can and they’ve reached the point where they’ve finally given up. If you’ve been say, arguing on the Internet with someone (never a good idea) and you just can’t get them to see reason then maybe you can just use one of these giving up Japanese emoticons and call it a day.
feature: For Japanese emoticons that are giving up you can usually use _’s for eyes that are low to the ground. You can also use and / or similar characters to show arms raised in defeat. Adding a ; for a drop of sweat always works too. You can also add a 尸 to make it look like the emoticon is waving a white flag in surrender.

description: The original table flipping emoticon is (╯°□°）╯︵ ┻━┻ followed by the guy who puts the table back ┬──┬◡ﾉ(° -°ﾉ) and then followed by flipping the guy who put the table back (╯°Д°）╯︵/(.□ . )
feature: There are however a ton of other table flipping emoticons, so many in fact that I felt they deserved their own category instead of being included in the other actions section. There are people flipping tables, bears flipping tables, flipping tables with magic and even tables flipping people in this category of Japanese emoticons. I also included in here some other things being flipped as well.

description: These kaomojis are sleeping, going to sleep or just waking up. Some of them are bundled up tight in bed, some are yawning and having a good stretch and some are completely passed out snoring away.
feature: These sleeping Japanese emoticons usually use some kind of horizontal line to indication closed eyes. You can also add bubbles or even Zs to indicate sleep. You can also use a ρ, ο or something like that to indicate yawning. c[_] can be used to indicate a cup of coffee and that is awesome.

description: Go crazy? Don’t mind if I do! If you have permission to go crazy or even if you don’t, then these are the kaomojis you want to use!
feature: This page features crazy looking Japanese emoticons. There are pretty much just any emoticon where they eyes are facing different directions or the emoticon is waving it’s arms around and freaking out. I managed to amass enough of these to justify having their own category.

description: These kaomojis are really shy. We’re not sure why they’re shy but they’re certainly cute. Covering their eyes like that, trying to hide… aww.
feature: The main thing about shy looking Japanese emoticons is the rosy cheeks. You can make rosy cheeks with a *, @, # or 〃. Adding a ; for a drop of sweat is always cute too. You can also use / and \ as arms where their eyes should be to show them covering their eyes.

description: Another new kaomoji category since I’ve now found a bunch of flexing Japanese emoticons showing off their muscles. These emoticons are also quite simple, just use ᕙ and ᕗ for the arms even if they do look pretty thin and not too muscular…
feature: Did you get your tickets to the gun show? ᕙ(⇀‸↼‶)ᕗ

description: Using these kaomojis is more fun than a barrel of monkeys! Especially since all of these Japanese emoticons are monkeys! How convenient. They’re quite cute too.
feature: You can easily make Japanese monkey emoticons by using @ symbols for ears. You can use pretty much any face and just add @ signs to make it into a monkey.

description: Happy kaomojis are probably the most common of all Japanese emoticons and that’s probably why this category is the largest one on the site. All of these Japanese emoticons are happy with happy smiling mouths or happy cute eyes full of joy and mirth.

I’ve just finished another giant site update the main feature of which is almost 1,000 new kaomoji emoticons added across almost every category on this site. That officially brings the total number of Japanese emoticons on this site to more than 4,000! 4,011 to be exact. Here are some of my favourite ones from the […]
feature: For happy looking emoticons you usually want to use eyes that are high up. The best characters to use for these are ^, ´, ｀, or ⌒ among others. The best characters to use for mouths are ones like ▽, ∀ or ω if you want to be cute. You can also add * or # for rosey cheeks or add waving arms with things like , /, ヽ or ﾉ. You can also always throw in stars or hearts too.

description: These kaomojis are writing things, things like stories, love letters, essays, reports or whatever you can imagine! If you want to show someone that you’re writing something (I don’t know, maybe that could happen) then use one of these emoticons.
feature: You can use φ, 〆 or ψ to make it look like your emoticon is writing. You can also use lines for a table or sheet of paper. There’s even an actual character for a pencil crazily enough! ✎

description: These poor kaomojis are dead. I’m not sure how they died but maybe it was from what some of the scared emoticons were scared of. Maybe some of those violent kaomojis killed them. Who knows but unfortunately for them they’re dead.
feature: You can easily make dead Japanese emoticons by just using x’s, +’s or *’s for eyes. Keeping the mouth low down with a _ makes it seem like the face is lying down on the ground.

description: This is a new category of Japanese emoticons that I’ve never encountered before. They look to me like clouds but I really have no idea what they’re supposed to be. I’m going to call them clouds anyways since they remind me of cute clouds with faces. You can pretty much turn any Japanese emoticon into a cloud if you use ꒰ and ꒱ for the sides of the face.
Kaomojis with moustaches are pretty awesome. The best part is that you can take pretty much any pre-existing Japanese emoticon and give it a mustache!
feature: You can basically take any of these emoticons and add a ┏ and a ┓ around the mouth to give it a somewhat Chinese looking or horseshoe-like mustache. You can also use any of these special characters that all make excellent mustaches: •̫̮ ˑ̭ ˑ̫ ︷ 灬 ~ ~ ﹏ ▂ ˒̫̮ ≀ ̼ ⁎̵̭ ⑉̈ ⌔̫ ̫ ̫̊ ̫ ·̼̮ 益 ₀̑

description: These are extra cute kissing kaomoji emoticons for those times you want to kiss something through the Internet but you can’t because that’s technically impossible… for now…
feature: For kissing emoticons you usually want to use something like ￣ or – for closed eyes. For a mouth use either ε or з. You can even add a “chu” which is the Japanese sound for a kiss or you can write it in Katakana by using チュ.

description: These Japanese emoticons are running. Why or from what we’re not sure but since so many of them seem to be getting out of here as fast as they can it might be a good idea to run away with them!
feature: You can use a bunch of ε and =s to show dust being kicked up from all that running. Or, if you want to get really fancy you can use ༅ and ༄ to show dust and whatnot in the wake of the running emoticon. Having alternating arms with one up and one down only makes it look more realistic too.

description: These Japanese emoticons are hugging things. Some of them might even be glomping things. Some look like they’d like a hug but they’re all by themselves. If you’re trying to hug something through the internet then you can distill those feelings down into one of these kaomojis and send that instead.
feature: You can use >, づ or ლ to indicate outstreatched arms. It’s also easy to put a second emoticon that’s the one being hugged. You can use any kind of expression for those ones for all kinds of hilarious different results.

description: These kaomojis are getting their dance on! Some are grooving to the music, some are raising the roof and some may even be gyrating… If you’d like to show off your sweet, sweet dance moves in the middle of some kind of post or text and you can’t because you’re a human in the real world then go ahead and use one of these dancing emoticons instead.
feature: For dancing Japanese emoticons you basically just take happy looking ones and add 〜, ノ or ヘ for arms. You can do two emoticons at once with the arms facing different ways to make it seem like the emoticon is dancing in both directions. Adding ” beside the arms makes it seem like it’s shaking too.

description: These poor kaomojis are scared. Why by looking at them I’d even say some of them are terrified. Look at them, some of them are even running away in fear! I don’t know what it is that has these Japanese emoticons so spooked but if you’re frightened by something, or maybe it’s Halloween or something then these are the perfect emoticons to use.
feature: For scared Japanese emoticons you pretty much just want to use / or to cover the emoticon’s eyes. You can also make pretty much anything with an open mouth such as Д and raised arms. Adding a ε＝ to make the kaomoji run away in fear is awesome too.

description: These Japanese emoticons are characters from various shows, things, Internet memes or whatever. They’re in different sections and they contain kaomoji from memes such as the Lenny face or “Raise Your Dongers!”. You’ll find other specific characters further down the page and various emoticons that I think are some kind of character but I’m not sure what they are. They’re very specialized looking faces that’s for sure.

description: This category of Japanese emoticons features kaomojis that are hungry. How do you know they’re hungry? We’ll you can tell because they’re licking their lips, they’re drooling or their mouths are open wide as if they’re ready to devour the whole world!
feature: If you want to make your own hungry looking kaomojis then the best thing to use as a ڡ for a mouth to show a tongue licking its lips. ۝ makes a fantastic wide open mouth symbol and ཀ is perfect for a drooling mouth.

description: I remember when someone first asked me to find a nose bleed emoticon. It took a while but I was eventually able to find one. Now I’ve found enough nosebleed kaomojis to justify having their own category. Especially because people keep asking for them.
feature: I still don’t really understand what the deal is with male anime characters getting nose bleeds when they’re aroused but I think I’ve accepted the fact that I never will and it’s just one of those quirky Japanese things… When it comes to these kind of things it’s best to not ask questions.

description: Cats are probably my favourite animal and what better way to celebrate that then with a giant page of kaomoji cat emoticons! Seriously, how cute are some of these kaomoji cats? Fun fact: the Japanese word for cat is “neko” and the sound they make in Japanese is “nya”. Feel free to add a little “nya” to any of these emoticons to make them extra Japanese.
feature: Cats are pretty much just most regular Japanese emoticons with =’s added to them as whiskers. ^’s can also be used for ears and you can use ･ｪ･ for a cat’s nose. Some of these cats get pretty elaborate and I’m highly impressed with some of them!

description: These Japanese emoticons are thinking really hard. Well actually some of them probably aren’t thinking that hard. Not only are some of these thinking in the standard sort of thinking way but some are thinking in an unimpressed way. They’re looking at something with shifty eyes as if they’re thinking “really, are you serious”. Some of them are even face palming because they just can’t believe whatever it is they’re thinking about.
feature: You can best express a look of deep thought by using ¬s for eyes. Most of these emoticons have an awesome unimpressed look. You can also make a thought bubble like ꒰…꒱ and put whatever you want inside it to show what they’re thinking about.

description: I’m impressed with how many Japanese rabbit emoticons there are here. It’s almost like rabbit island in Japan! But seriously, how cute are some of these kaomoji bunny rabbits?
feature: For rabbit Japanese emoticons you want to use an X or ㅅ for a mouth. You can use pretty much any thing for eyes but don’t forget to make ears. Downward slashes, Us or ⌒s make excellent rabbit ears.

description: Kaomoji friends look like they’re so happy together, having lots of fun and all that. Some of them are kind of sad though but look, they’re being comforted by a friend. How nice. If you want to show off or express friendship then these are the emoticons for you!
feature: These emoticons are really just happy looking ones holding up their hands to each other. You can combine pretty much any emoticons and join their hands together with a 人, /＼ or メ.

description: These kaomojis are hiding. Why are they hiding? We’ll that could be for one of many reasons. Maybe they’re scared, maybe they’re spying on you, maybe they’re up to no good. Whatever the reason is if you need a Japanese emoticon that looks like it’s sticking it’s face out from behind a wall off in the distance then you’ve come to the right place!
feature: You can take pretty much any Japanese emoticon and cut it in half or into some other size with a | to make it seem as if it’s peaking out from behind a wall. You get bonus points if you use a few more characters to draw some of the wall too.

description: This category has Japanese emoticons and kaomoji that belong to different holidays such as Christmas, Halloween, New Years, etc. I’ve broken down each holiday into it’s own section of emoticons.

description: This is the Internet’s largest list of over 6,700 specially selected kaomoji Japanese emoticons. The categories from this site are listed in alphabetical order as you scroll down the page.

If you’ve noticed new kaomoji emoticons and categories slowly appearing on the site it’s because for the last week or so I’ve been working on the biggest site update yet! I’ve added over 2,500 new kaomoji emoticons and 6 new categories bringing the grand total of Japanese emoticons on this site 6,727! My next goal […]

Movember is a global men’s health charity where men grow a moustache and women support the moustache to raise awareness for men’s health issues such as prostate cancer, testicular cancer and mental health problems. Movember takes place every November and is about bringing back the moustache (aka the Mo), having fun, creating awareness and raising […]

description: These kaomoji are laughing at things, things like jokes, humorous situations, comedy or maybe some of them are laughing at another person because they’re jerks! If you saw something on the Internet that’s funny and you want to impress everyone with a some fancy Japanese emoticon and make everyone jealous since all they know how to do is type lol then you definitely want to use these emoticons.
feature: These are essentially happy looking emoticons with an open mouth. You can also use 艸 to make it look like the emoticon is covering its mouth with its hands. Some of them are pretty elaborate and have flapping arms and some even have little “ha ha ha”s or “ho ho ho”s.

description: These kaomojis are surprised. You might even say that some of them are shocked! Shocked and Appalled even! What has these Japanese emoticons so shocked? That we’ll never know but if someone ever delivers news that you find surprising or shocking then you’ll want to reply back to them with one of these emoticons.
feature: For shocked or surprised Japanese emoticons you mainly want to use an open mouth such as a □ or Д. Or you can just use an o, capital O or 0 for a big wide open shocked mouth. You can also use characters to show raised arms. A lot of surprised emoticons also have a Σ in them. I think that’s supposed to indicate holding a hand to your head or something. Exclamation marks are always good to include too.

description: So many of these kaomoji emoticons are crying. Alas all is not lost because not all of these are sad. Some of these emoticons are crying with joy! If you want to express tears for any reason whether it be joy or sadness then these are the Japanese emoticons you want to use.
feature: There were enough of these crying Japanese emoticons to justify separating them from the sad category into their own crying category. Plus not all crying emoticons are sad, some are crying tears of joy. Most of these though are essentially sad emotions that are crying. You can usually show tears with a T, ; or a ╥.

description: These smug little Japanese emoticons think they’re better than you! Are they? Probably not. Are you better than someone else? Probably. Throw that in their face with one of these smug kaomoji emoticons.
feature: For smug Japanese emoticons you want to use closed eyes like ￣. Anything you can do to put their nose up in the air too definitely helps.

description: Japanese fish emoticons are somewhat different as they’re from the side and very much look like swimming fish. You can add or subtract brackets to change the length of the fish. It’s also very easy to make crabs and whales as well. Plus if you look closely you might find a kaomoji frog!

These kaomojis are winking suggestively at someone. Well it might not be suggestive but that’s probably the only reason I know for winking. If you want to wink to someone through the internet with emoticons than use one of these instead of the standard ;) and you may just blow their mind!
feature: For winking Japanese emoticons you can take pretty much any relatively happy looking face and make one of the eyes closed by using a flat character like -. You can also use stars which for some reason signify winks.

description: These kaomojis are full of love (or maybe they’re just infatuated) and if you’re full of love then you go right ahead and use some of these to express that love! Some of these emoticons are even in cute little couples. Some of them are even hugging or kissing!
feature: For Japanese emoticons that express infatuation or love you pretty much just need to add hearts to happy looking emoticons. You can also add rosey cheeks or even the Chinese character for love, 愛.

description: I have no words to describe these freaky as heck bleeding eye Japanese emoticon things. I don’t know what kind of messed up mind could create these or why so I’ve decided to call this category of emoticons wtf. Aside from those emoticons you’ll find some other rather dirty ones and a few other messed up things in kaomoji form.
These Japanese emoticons are raising a hand in a salute. They might be military kaomoji or they might just be being cute.
feature: Yes sir! I’m working on it! ( ・∀・ )ゞ

description: These Japanese emoticons are wearing sunglasses. Maybe they think they’re being cool. Maybe they’re douchebags. Maybe the sun’s just too bright. Either way, if you need kaomoji with eye wear this is the place to look. Also including regular glasses and monocle’s for that extra classy look!
These kaomoji dogs are pretty cute. There’s all kinds of dogs here including Jake from Adventure Time!
feature: The main thing with Japanese dog emoticons is the ears. Use a U for big floppy ears, u for little ears or even V’s for ears as well. You can also use ∵ on either side of the mouth to make it look more dog like. ᴥ is perfect for a cute little doggy nose and ૮ and ა make very dog-like ears as well.

description: These kaomoji birds are really cute. This page has ducks, owls, baby birds, flappy birds, all kinds! There’s even a bat down there at the bottom of the page. It snuck in because it has wings…
feature: You can create Japanese emoticon birds by using Θ for a beak (works great for baby birds) or pointy characters like < or ▼. If you use those you can use pretty much anything else for the rest of it but don’t tell anyone, keep it a secret.

description: These are some very musical kaomoji emoticons. Some are singing and some are whistling, all of them are being pretty cute. One or two of them may even be playing a musical instrument. There’s also a DJ kaomoji in there which is pretty awesome.
feature: For singing Japanese emoticons you can basically take any dancing Japanese emoticon, give it an open mouth with something like a Ｏ, △ or □ and adding a musical note like ♪ before or after the face always helps too. You can make whistling emoticons by using a ε for a mouth.

description: This is a category of kaomojis that are hurt in various ways. They might be hurt physically or maybe they’ve been hurt emotionally. Some of them are sick which is kind of a sort of hurt. There weren’t really enough sick emoticons to justify their own category so I’m including them here with the hurt ones. A few of these emoticons have even fallen over in pain. Those poor little Japanese emoticons…
feature: To make hurt Japanese emoticons all you really need to do is add stars to angry or sad looking emoticons. If you can make it look like the emoticon is lying on the ground then that’s even better.

description: Why are there so many of these sad kaomoji emoticons?! What did you guys do to make them so sad? Well whatever you did I’m not pleased, kind of like these emoticons. But I guess if you’re feeling sad then these are the Japanese emoticons you’ll want to use. Try to cheer up though, this site has so many other happier kaomojis too.
feature: The main part of sad Japanese emoticons is the tears. These are usually shown with a T or sometimes a ;. You can also throw other small circles around the outside of the face to show tears flying as well. You can also use characters like / and ＼ to cover up their eyes to make it look like the emoticon is sobbing. You can pretty much use whatever you want for a mouth. I’m really impressed that someone managed to come up with some kind of way to make it look like the tears are spilling down onto multiple lines below the line the kaomoji is on. I have no idea how they did that.

description: Waving kaomojis! Some are waving hello and some are waving goodbye. Some of them are waving to get your attention or distract you from something. Maybe some of these are famous and are waving to their fans. Some of them are probably lonely and waving at some people to hopefully get some friends and that’s kind of sad.
feature: These are pretty much standard happy or joyful emoticons usually with a forward or back slash for an arm. You can also use characters such as ヾ to make it seem as if the emoticon is shaking it’s arm. These emoticons function in both the hello and goodbye positions.

description: You can basically take any Japanese emoticon and add a cup to it with a 口, 旦 or 且 to make it look like it’s drinking or use ♨ to indicate hot food or drink.
feature: I wonder what kaomoji food or drink tastes like…

description: This page is full of magic Japanese emoticons. Witches, wizards, magical girls, people who just somehow found some magic wands and aren’t quite sure how they work, etc. I’ve now kind of found enough of these to justify them having their own category.
feature: For these kaomojis you really just need to add some wand like characters and then some stars and sparkles to pretty much any other emoticon.

description: There were enough high energy excited looking emoticons in the happy category to justify the creation of this excited category. To make your own excited Japanese emoticons you simply need to make happy ones with > and <s or ≧ and ≦s for eyes. It also helps if you use slashes or characters like ノ, ヽ or ヾ to show that they’re throwing their arms up in excitement. Don’t forget that adding stars and other flourishes can only lead to more excitement!

Movember, which takes place during the month of November is when people from all over the world band together and raise money and awareness for men’s health issues, specifically prostate cancer and testicular cancer.
feature: Men grow a “Mo” which is slang for moustache for 30 days to become walking and talking advertisements for men’s health causes.

category: A Whole Bunch of New Emoticons!
description: Here’s another giant round of Japanese emoticons that have now been added to the site. All of these were suggested by you guys, the readers of this site. Thanks a lot and feel free to keep suggesting more.
feature: Mukman sent me this Japanese emoticon kicking another emoticon.
